06442nam a22007695i 9780773549456DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735494567 a10.1515/97807735494562doi  a(DE-B1597)654916  a(OCoLC)1030716674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJV7225.2 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a325.710905100aTwenty-First-Century Immigration to North America :bNewcomers in Turbulent Times /ced. by Victoria M. Esses, Donald E. Abelson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Ethnic History ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tTwenty-First-Century Immigration to North America -- tOverview of Immigration Policy in Canada and the United States -- tManaging Immigration: A Short History of Turbulence and Public Policy -- tUS Immigration Reform -- tEconomic Aspects of North American Immigration -- tEconomic Outcomes of Immigrants in Canada -- tImmigrant Skill Utilization: Trends and Policy Issues -- tThe Impact of Immigration on the US Labour Market: What Have We Learned since 2000 and What Do We Need to Do Next? -- tSocio-Cultural Aspects of North American Immigration -- tAssimilation and Its Discontented -- tMuslim Immigration to North America: The Rise of New Challenges and the Need for New Perspectives -- tComparing Immigrant Children in Canada and the United States: Similarities and Differences -- tPrecarious Migration: Refugees and Undocumented Workers in North America -- tFilling the Federal Policy Void: State and Local Responses to Undocumented Immigration in the United States -- tValue Conflict in Turbulent Times: Shifting Policies on Refugees, Asylum-Seekers, and Undocumented Migrants -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHuman migration has reached an unprecedented level, and the numbers are expected to continue growing into the foreseeable future. Host societies and migrants face challenges in ensuring that the benefits of migration accrue to both parties, and that economic and socio-cultural costs are minimized. An insightful comparative examination of the policies and practices that manage and support immigrants, Twenty-First-Century Immigration to North America identifies and addresses issues that arose in the early years of the twenty-first century and considers what to expect in the years ahead. The volume begins with an overview of immigration policies and practices in the United States and Canada, then moves to an investigation of the economic and socio-cultural aspects, and concludes with a dialogue on precarious migration. Taking a multidisciplinary approach, the editors include research from the areas of psychology, political science, economics, sociology, and public policy. Underscoring the complicated nature of immigration, this collection aims to foster further discussion and inspire future research in the United States and Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantszCanadaxHistoryy21st century. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aImmigrants; Canada; History, 21st century. 0aImmigrants; United States; History, 21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAbelson, Donald E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbelson, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeach, Charles M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurstein, Meyer, econtrib